%C2%A0%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EThe%20case%20for%20Taylor%20Swift's%20millipede%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EA%20Virginia%20Tech%20researcher%20made%20headlines%20for%20naming%20a%20millipede%20after%20Taylor%20Swift.%20It%20seemed%20like%20a%20smart%20move%2C%20as%20everyday%20arthropods%20rarely%20make%20history%2C%20and%20this%20sort%20of%20publicity%20can%20help%20bring%20awareness%2C%20according%20to%20a%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fconbio.onlinelibrary.wiley.com%2Fdoi%2Fabs%2F10.1111%2Fcobi.14184%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erecent%20paper%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EUniversity%20of%20Oxford%20biologist%20Katie%20Blake%20and%20her%20co-authors%20found%20that%20species%20with%20celebrity%20names%20had%20almost%20three%20times%20as%20many%20page%20views%20on%20Wikipedia%20as%20non-famously%20monikered%20control%20species.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20whether%20those%20views%20actually%20translate%20to%20better%20conservation%20efforts%20needs%20further%20study.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%223797%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20tiger%20shark%20swims%20close%20to%20the%20camera%20in%20the%20Bahamas.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65444d193cc84b4dfafb7ba4%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222847%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3ETiger%20sharks%20(Galeocerdo%20cuvier)%20were%20named%20for%20one%20of%20the%20founders%20of%20comparative%20anatomy%2C%20Georges%20Cuvier.%3Cp%3EAndre%20Seale%2FVW%20PICS%2FUniversal%20Images%20Group%20via%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%20it's%20not%20clear%20if%20the%20attention%20is%20always%20positive%2C%20especially%20if%20the%20celebrity%20figure%20is%20more%20infamous%20than%20famous.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWe%20need%20more%20work%20to%20better%20understand%20how%20species%20are%20affected%20when%20named%20after%20someone%20who%20is%20fairly%20controversial%2C%26quot%3B%20Blake%20said.%20%26quot%3BNot%20only%20in%20terms%20of%20attitudes%20towards%20these%20species%2C%20but%20conservation%20action%2C%20too%2C%20where%20needed.%26quot%3B%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20Blake%20thinks%20celebrity%20names%20can%20draw%20attention%20to%20amphibians%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Foctopuses-crabs-lobsters-recognized-as-sentient-beings-in-uk-2021-11%5C%22%3Einvertebrates%3C%2Fa%3E%20%26quot%3Bwho%20aren't%20exactly%20the%20public's%20favorite%20taxa%2C%20the%20consequences%20of%20naming%20them%20after%20someone%20who%20is%20disliked%20may%20worsen%20such%20species'%20conservation%20status.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat's%20one%20reason%20why%20some%20scientists%20want%20to%20rename%20a%20blind%20cave%20beetle.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EThe%20push%20to%20save%20a%20beetle%20named%20after%20Hitler%C2%A0%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EPart%20of%20a%20scientific%20name's%20appeal%20is%20that%20it's%20unchanging%20and%20the%20same%20in%20every%20language.%20But%20recently%2C%20researchers%20have%20begun%20proposing%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com%2Fdoi%2Ffull%2F10.1002%2Ftax.12821%5C%22%3Emaking%20changes%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20%26quot%3Bscientific%20names%20that%20commemorate%20historical%20individuals%20who%20committed%20egregious%20crimes%20against%20humanity.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EChristopher%20Bae%2C%20a%20professor%20of%20anthropology%20at%20the%20University%20of%20Hawai'i%20at%20Mano%2C%20and%20his%20colleagues%20were%20more%20specific%2C%20stating%20that%20names%20with%20%26quot%3Btyrants%2C%20dictators%2C%20colonialists%2C%20and%20slave%20traders%26quot%3B%20should%20be%20changed.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESome%20examples%20include%20Adolf%20Hitler%2C%20Cecil%20Rhodes%2C%20and%20George%20Hibbert%2C%20all%20of%20whom%20have%20species%20named%20after%20them.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHitler%20actually%20has%3Cs%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fs%3E%20two%20insects%20named%20after%20him.%20One%2C%20the%20Rochlingia%20hitleri%2C%20has%20been%20extinct%20for%20millions%20of%20years.%20The%20other%20is%20a%20rare%20cave-dwelling%20beetle%2C%20Anophthalmus%20hitleri.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221999%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Rocky%20formations%20in%20Krizna%20Jama%20Cave%2C%20Cross%20Cave%2C%20in%20Grahovo%2C%20Slovenia.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65444e503cc84b4dfafb7bfa%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221499%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20blind%20cave%20beetle%20is%20found%20in%20only%20a%20few%20caves%20in%20Slovenia.%3Cp%3ESergio%20Pitamitz%2FVWPics%2FUniversal%20Images%20Group%20via%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EScientists%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.science.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1126%2Fscience.358.6367.1116%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ehave%20warned%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20the%20cave%20beetle%20is%20threatened%20by%20poachers.%20%26quot%3BThese%20collectors%20are%20going%20out%20and%20collecting%20and%20then%20selling%20them%20on%20the%20internet%20to%20Neo-Nazis%20because%20they're%20memorabilia%20now%2C%26quot%3B%20Bae%20said.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnother%20example%20is%20the%20many%20species%20named%20for%20the%20imperialist%20Cecil%20John%20Rhodes%20who%20pushed%20for%20British%20expansion%20into%20southern%20Africa%20and%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oriel.ox.ac.uk%2Fcecil-rhodes-racial-segregation-in-the-cape-colony-and-violence-in-zimbabwe%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esupported%3C%2Fa%3E%20racial%20segregation.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHis%20name%20is%20splashed%20across%20the%20biological%20world%2C%20including%20many%20plant%20names%20stemming%20from%20the%20Rhodesia%20region%2C%20what%20is%20now%20known%20as%20Zimbabwe%20and%20Zambia.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERight%20now%2C%20the%20debate%20over%20whether%20to%20use%20a%20Rhodes-derived%20name%20is%20especially%20pertinent%20for%20paleoanthropologists%20who%20study%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2F40000-year-bone-hints-humans-neanderthals-shared-cave-culture-2023-8%5C%22%3Eearly%20human%20ancestors%3C%2Fa%3E.%20There's%20a%20label%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhuman-ancestors-were-down-1300-faced-extinction-900000-years-ago-2023-9%5C%22%3EHomo%20heidelbergensis%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20that's%20such%20a%20mishmash%20of%20species%2C%20that%20it's%20no%20longer%20a%20meaningful%20designation%2C%20according%20to%20Bae.%20Instead%2C%20researchers%20want%20to%20introduce%20a%20new%20name%20for%20an%20ancestor%20of%20modern%20humans.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221733%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22View%20of%20a%20skull%20of%20an%20adult%20Homo%20heidelbergensis%20found%20in%20Spain%20in%201992%20sits%20on%20display%20at%20the%20Museum%20of%20Human%20Evolution%20in%202010.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64f4bf9b781926001910b4bc%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221300%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20skull%20of%20an%20adult%20Homo%20heidelbergensis%20found%20in%20Spain%20in%201992.%20Paleoanthropologists%20are%20debating%20what%20to%20change%20the%20species'%20name%20to.%3Cp%3ECESAR%20MANSO%2FAFP%20via%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20they%20were%20to%20follow%20the%20traditional%20naming%20practice%2C%20then%20the%20International%20Code%20of%20Zoological%20Nomenclature's%20rules%20state%20that%20the%20first%20name%20given%20to%20a%20species%20gets%20priority%20on%20being%20the%20scientific%20name%2C%20so%20the%20species%20would%20be%20called%20Homo%20rhodesiensis.%20A%20human%20skull%20found%20in%20Zambia%20was%20given%20that%20name%20in%201921.%3Cstrong%3E%20%3Cbr%3E%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20Bae%20and%20many%20of%20his%20colleagues%20aren't%20eager%20to%20start%20using%20the%20name%20Homo%20rhodesiensis%2C%20especially%20because%20of%20the%20significance%20of%20the%20species.%20%26quot%3BThis%20guy%20had%20some%20real%20serious%20issues%2C%26quot%3B%20Bae%20said%20of%20Rhodes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEarlier%20this%20year%2C%20Bae%20and%20over%20a%20dozen%20other%20paleoanthropologists%20gathered%20to%20discuss%20the%20issue%2C%20and%20it%20was%20nearly%20unanimous.%20Almost%20no%20one%20was%20in%20favor%20of%20using%20the%20Rhodes-derived%20name.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnother%20name%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fnew-human-ancestor-species-proposed-homo-bodoensis-2021-10%5C%22%3EHomo%20bodoensis%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20named%20for%20Bodo%20D'ar%2C%20Ethiopia%2C%20where%20the%20skull%20was%20found%2C%20has%20been%20proposed%20instead.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EWhat%20would%20it%20take%20to%20change%20a%20species%3Cstrong%3E'%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20name%3F%C2%A0%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221440%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20side-by-side%20of%20Jimmy%20Buffett%20playing%20guitar%20on%20stage%20and%20the%20yellow%20Cayo%20margarita%20snail%20under%20the%20sea.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65444c4d3cc84b4dfafb7b6b%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221080%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EIn%20honor%20of%20Jimmy%20Buffett%E2%80%99s%20%E2%80%9CMargaritaville%2C%E2%80%9D%20scientists%20named%20this%20yellow%20snail%20Cayo%20margarita.%3Cp%3EHal%20Horowitz%2FWireImage%2FGetty%20Images%3B%20R.%20Bieler%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20are%20hundreds%20of%20thousands%20of%20species%20with%20eponymous%20names%2C%20according%20to%20the%20ICZN's%20estimate.%20But%20Bae%20thinks%20only%20a%20fraction%20of%20them%20reach%20the%20level%20of%20Hitler%2C%20Hibbert%2C%20and%20Rhodes.%20To%20protect%20against%20frivolous%20changes%2C%20Bae%20and%20his%20co-authors%20called%20for%20an%20ethics%20committee%20to%20review%20proposals.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BNobody's%20going%20to%20really%20want%20to%20go%20after%20every%20single%20name%20out%20there%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%20%26quot%3BIt's%20really%20going%20to%20be%20the%20egregious%20ones%20that%20need%20to%20be%20looked%20at%20more%20carefully.%26quot%3B%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222005%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20brontosaurus%20skeleton%20on%20display%20at%20the%20Peabody%20Museum%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F654452da3cc84b4dfafb7ced%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221500%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20brontosaurus%20is%20just%20one%20animal%20to%20have%20its%20scientific%20name%20changed%20(and%20then%20changed%20back%20again).%3Cp%3EGeorge%20Rinhart%2FCorbis%20via%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20names%20can%20be%20changed.%20Consider%20the%20Brontosaurus%2C%20which%20was%20a%20genus%20of%20dinosaur%20that%20was%20lumped%20together%20with%20the%20Apatosaurus%20and%20then%20separated%20again%20in%202015.%20The%20alterations%20are%20often%20made%20for%20scientific%20reasons%20but%20not%20always.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20American%20Ornithological%20Society%20is%20in%20the%20process%20of%20changing%20the%20common%20English%20names%20of%20bird%20species%20named%20after%20people.%20The%20organization%20Bird%20Names%20for%20Birds%20has%20pushed%20for%20the%20change%20because%20many%20of%20the%20animals%20are%20named%20for%20people%20who%20enslaved%20others%20or%20dug%20up%20Native%20American%20graves.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20the%20birds'%20scientific%20names%20will%20remain%2C%20as%20they%20are%20much%20more%20difficult%20to%20change%2C%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.npr.org%2F2023%2F11%2F01%2F1209660753%2Fthese-american-birds-and-dozens-more-will-be-renamed-to-remove-human-monikers%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ENPR%20reported%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EDown%20with%20all%20eponyms%3F%C2%A0%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWe%20already%20have%20thousands%20of%20species%20named%20for%20people%20who%20are%20now%20obscure%2C%26quot%3B%20Stephen%20B.%20Heard%20wrote%20in%20his%20book%20%26quot%3BCharles%20Darwin's%20Barnacle%20and%20David%20Bowie's%20Spider%3A%20How%20Scientific%20Names%20Celebrate%20Adventurers%2C%20Heroes%2C%20and%20Even%20a%20Few%20Scoundrels.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat%20a%20celebrity%20might%20fade%20from%20public%20consciousness%20isn't%20the%20worst%20thing%20that%20could%20happen%2C%20though.%20Case%20in%20point%2C%20Hitler's%20beetle.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EChances%20are%20most%20celebrities%20with%20eponymous%20species%20won't%20leave%20a%20legacy%20as%20tarnished%20as%20some%20powerful%20men%20of%20the%20past.%20Yet%20societal%20norms%20do%20change%2C%20and%20it's%20easy%20to%20see%20how%20some%20famous%20people's%20reputations%20changed%20after%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhow-the-metoo-movement-started-where-its-headed-tarana-burke-time-person-of-year-women-2017-12%5C%22%3E%23MeToo%20movement%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20for%20example.%C2%A0%20%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%20some%20researchers%20would%20prefer%20to%20correct%20the%20imbalance%20of%20species%20named%20mostly%20after%20European%20men%20from%20the%2019th%20and%2020th%20centuries%2C%20instead%20naming%20more%20species%20after%20women%20and%20native%20scientists.%20Or%20perhaps%20changing%20existing%20eponyms%20to%20be%20more%20inclusive.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAs%20some%20researchers%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com%2Fdoi%2F10.1002%2Ftax.12742%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Enoted%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20%26quot%3Btheir%20names%20will%20not%20be%20eliminated%20from%20history%3A%20they%20will%20simply%20move%20into%20synonymy%2C%26quot%3B%20That%20is%2C%20there%20could%20one%20day%20be%20a%20footnote%20indicating%20that%20the%20species%20was%20formerly%20known%20as%20Hitler's%20beetle.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fspecies-name-celebrity-awaren