hat%20the%20onboard%20crew%20and%20space%20station%20are%20safe%20with%20no%20action%20required%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20NASA%20on%20its%20blog.%3Cbr%3E%5Cn%3Cbr%3E%5Cn%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20toolbag%2C%20resembling%20a%20white%20satchel%2C%20exhibits%20surprising%20brightness%2C%20just%20below%20the%20threshold%20of%20visibility%20to%20the%20naked%20eye.%20This%20brightness%20allows%20observers%20to%20spot%20it%20using%20binoculars%2C%20with%20a%20visual%20magnitude%20of%20around%206%2C%20slightly%20less%20bright%20than%20the%20ice%20giant%20Uranus%2C%20according%20to%20EarthSky.%20To%20track%20the%20bag%2C%20observers%20can%20locate%20the%20ISS%2C%20the%20third-brightest%20object%20in%20the%20night%20sky%2C%20using%20NASA's%20Spot%20the%20Station%20tool.%20The%20bag%20orbits%20Earth%20two%20to%20four%20minutes%20ahead%20of%20the%20ISS.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EJapanese%20astronaut%20Satoshi%20Furukawa%20spotted%20the%20bag%20floating%20over%20Mount%20Fuji%20last%20week%2C%20confirming%20its%20tracking%2C%20as%20noted%20by%20astronaut%20Meganne%20Christian.%20The%20lost%20toolbag%20is%20expected%20to%20remain%20in%20orbit%20for%20some%20months%20before%20descending%20rapidly%20and%20meeting%20its%20demise%20in%20Earth's%20atmospheric%20inferno.%20Preliminary%20estimates%20suggest%20the%20toolbag%20should%20reenter%20the%20atmosphere%20around%20March%202024%2C%20according%20to%20EarthSky.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%20class%3D%5C%22twitter-tweet%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20lang%3D%5C%22en%5C%22%20dir%3D%5C%22ltr%5C%22%3ELast%20seen%20by%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftwitter.com%2FAstro_Satoshi%3Fref_src%3Dtwsrc%255Etfw%5C%22%3E%40Astro_Satoshi%3C%2Fa%3E%20while%20floating%20over%20Mount%20Fuji%20%F0%9F%97%BB%20the%20'Orbital%20Police'%20can%20confirm%20that%20the%20lost%20EVA%20gear%20is%20being%20tracked%20%F0%9F%AB%A1%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ft.co%2Fwz4MITmAfM%5C%22%3Ehttps%3A%2F%2Ft.co%2Fwz4MITmAfM%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ft.co%2Feksfu9fP